{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501134","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501134"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:23:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:23:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1722"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1722"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.3,0.03,0.01,0.02,0.65]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1722"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83439"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1722"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1722"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68340"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"2210"},{"type":"tags","id":"4183"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5492"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7496"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28465"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83439"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ERenal cell carcinoma can present in several different ways.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common mode of presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haematuria","Flank pain","Intermittent fever","Abdominal mass","Incidental detection on imaging"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn a 2020 cohort study, 60% of RCCs were \u003Cstrong\u003Edetected incidentally via non-invasive imaging\u003C/strong\u003E, as part of investigation for other non-specific abdominal symptoms. Presence of risk factors such as smoking, obesity, family history, and polycystic kidney disease is an important consideration for suspicion of an RCC and need for imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaematuria\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eflank pain\u003C/strong\u003E, \u003Cstrong\u003Eintermittent fever\u003C/strong\u003E, and a palpable\u003Cstrong\u003E abdominal mass\u003C/strong\u003E are late signs of aggressive disease and are considerably rarer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWith the current enthusiasm for performing a CT scan on every patient who enters a general practitioner\u0027s clinic or an emergency department, the likelihood of an incidental finding is high. It has been estimated that incidental findings can be identified on about 10% of all CT scans and perhaps up to 40% of chest and abdominal scans. Such is the case with renal cell carcinoma; many of these lesions are detected well before they produce any clinical symptoms or signs. In most cases, the incidental findings are innocent and never cause the patient any symptoms - such as renal cysts.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The classic triad of flank pain, haematuria, and abdominal mass is not always present in patients with renal cell carcinoma, and suggests advanced disease.","Renal cell carcinoma is often detected incidentally during imaging for unrelated conditions, highlighting the importance of imaging in early diagnosis."],"references":["Ljungberg B, Albiges L, Abu-Ghanem Y, Bedke J, Capitanio U, Dabestani S, et al. European Association of Urology Guidelines on Renal Cell Carcinoma: The 2022 Update. European Urology. 2022;82(4):399-410. Available from: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0302283822016761?via%3Dihub","Rao K, Royce PL. Incidentally detected small renal masses - Investigation and management. Australian Family Physician Vol. 40, No. 10, October 2011. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/download/documents/AFP/2011/October/201110rao.pdf","Andrawes P, Picon AI, Shariff MA, Azab B, von Waagner W, Demissie S, Fasanya C. CT scan incidental findings in trauma patients: does it impact hospital length of stay? Trauma Surg Acute Care Open. 2017 Sep 14;2(1):e000101. doi: 10.1136/tsaco-2017-000101. PMID: 29766099; PMCID: PMC5877912. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29766099/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68340"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1722"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68340"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-04T18:35:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-04T18:37:50+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1722"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83439"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"he